note = |Spanish red iron oxide is prefered. I have found that my blue celadon
note = |glaze, which is very similar to others given to you, likes all the
note = |reduction I can give it. I fire blue celadon pieces in the same
note = |firings I go for carbon trapping with my shinos. The extra reduction
note = |along with a good thick application of the blue celadon glaze, I
note = |think, encourages the bubbles trapped in the glaze which gives it a
note = |nice softness to the glossy glaze. I introduce a heavy reduction at
note = |cone 010 through to cone 06 then lighten up a bit for the rest of the
note = |firing. Also, drips melt out and do not show. Despite the only
note = |average amount of clay in the glaze, but high amount of feldspar and
note = |flint, the glaze does not run at all at cone 10 EPK helps and use
note = |Spanish Red Iron oxide and do not get any speckling. I feel the blue
note = |celadon glaze is much nicer on porcelain. You may need to add a
note = |suspender, I don't though. I have substituted Strontium Carbonate for
note = |half of the Barium and all of the Barium at 1 part Barium to 3/4
note = |parts Strontium and received just as nice results. I have the
note = |understanding from talking with other colleagues that the glaze
note = |should be safe from Barium poisoning because it is a glossy glaze
note = |where enough silica molecules have combined with the Barium molecules
note = |to make it stable. But, I have never had it tested. Does anyone know
note = |if this is true or not? Please reply. Enjoy, Cone 10 down, submitted
note = |by: Steve Loucks e-mail: STEVLOUCKS@aol.com

