note = |(Mile Hi in Denver has Ilmenite). Likes a fast cooling to develop
note = |that electric blue. One dip gives you brown, two dips a deep blue.
note = |Tends to break on ridges. Where real heavy you get white. Flows quite
note = |a bit, especially combined with other glazes. Watch your bottom
note = |feet,try to give it a good foot or a strong ridge to stop flow.
note = |Tapering the bottom edge with a straight edge helps too. Otherwise
note = |your shelf will be a beautiful shade of blue. If thick, tends to
note = |pinhole, likes to dry and be rubbed out before firing. Tempermental
note = |glaze---can crawl just enough to make you crazy generally under rims
note = |and on the inside of rims....probably is thicker there and shrinks
note = |when drying. To Mix, we've found it best to dissolve the Cornwall
note = |first and let set a bit, then add everything else. Screen through a
note = |40 once and an 80mesh twice for finest crystalization. This is a
note = |compilation of several background messages re: the Conrad Moonlight.
note = |We use Conrads Moonlight (which was discussed about 6 months ago
note = |here) with about 1/2%cobalt Carb. added. It's a cone 10 glaze. I
note = |first started using it in electric firing, and a year ago switched to
note = |gas. At first in the gas, it was muddier and tended toward rutile
note = |blue-green. Then, experimenting, we cooled the kiln faster to match
note = |the curve of the electrics. Voila, nice sharp crystals and blue. It
note = |also seems to be quite sensitive to temperature, over fire it and it
note = |grabs iron from anywhere and goes blue green or brownish. I also
note = |might note that it is quite sensitive to application. It must go on
note = |thick to develop a good blue. (even sometimes giving almost purple).
note = |Thick in the bucket, double dip as soon as the sheen leaves, dry
note = |completely, then rub lightly everywhere and especially on compund
note = |curves. This is a Cornwall recipe and tends to crawl if not thorughly
note = |bonded to the clay surface. The thickness required doesn't help.
note = |Don't know what it might do at c6 but if you can get it there, the
note = |above notes might help. One note, I mentioned that it's sensitive to
note = |temp. It's happiest between 9-1/2 and 10-1/2. Also we use it on a
note = |white stoneware. On iron body clays, it tends toward blue green or
note = |brown-green...not too pretty. Joyce brought up a good pointThe rutile
note = |blue Moonlight from Conrad (G375) is r understand, most rutile blues
note = |are. The way we work around this is to provide a ridge at the foot
note = |and, when Betsy applies the glaze, she takes a stainless rib and
note = |carves a taper into the ridge. Sounds time consuming, and is, but it
note = |goes pretty fast after you've done (not had) a few. The main time we
note = |lose pieces from running now is where there's an overlap with another
note = |glaze, especially Temmoku. But by keeping it high on the pot, it can
note = |be controlled. Good Luck. It can be a fantastic rutile blue, best
note = |I've seen. I'll be off the list for a week, at Rosen, but will pull
note = |digests during the week. Tom Wirt Clay Coyote Pottery Hutchinson, MN
note = |claypot@hutchtel.net

