note = |Cost/kg 0.24 Si:Al 7.71 SiB:Al 7.71 Expan 6.72 My celedon formula is
note = |posted at the end of this message. It's a lime green celedon the way
note = |I color it. I use 5% of a native Oregon clay that is very high in
note = |Iron. You could maybe get the same color with 5% or so of Alberta
note = |slip, or Albany. 1 to 2% additions of red or black iron will give
note = |celedons. It is often said that black iron oxide gives bluer
note = |celedons, so you might want to try that. It is important to keep a
note = |glaze's content of titanium at a near zero level to develop blue
note = |celedons as well. Titanium will encourage green. I ran your Neph Sy
note = |celedon through Insight and you could reduce the crazing and maybe
note = |eliminate it by the direct substitution of potash feldspar for the
note = |Neph Sy. You might want to try both Custer and G-200. Custer is
note = |higher in silica and would be the most effective one to lower the
note = |glazes expansion. G-200 will give a bit better melt I
note = |think..........Craig craig martell <ashglaze@teleport.com>

