note = |
note = | Add colorants for the real action!
note = |
note = |*How long have you been using this glaze?
note = | 8-10 years
note = |
note = |*Where is it used?  Bob Kavanagh's studio.
note = |
note = |*Where did this recipe come from?  I developed it over a few years.
note = |
note = |*What do you like most about this glaze?  It is stable, adaptable, accepts diverse
note = |colors well, applies easily, is virtually fault free - a good friend.
note = |
note = |*Does this glaze tend to craze/crawl/pinhole/etc.?
note = | With the majolica, it may crawl if the glaze is applied VERY thickly.
note = |
note = |*How do different firing temperatures/atmospheres affect the glaze?
note = | It may be used in reduction as well as in oxidation, although I now
note = |use it only in oxidation.  I developed it while I was working in a
note = |reducing atmosphere.  The differences between oxidation and reduction
note = |lie in the clarity of the glaze (much clearer in oxidation) and of
note = |course the impact of reduction on iron bearing oxides.
note = |
note = |*How does the glaze behave on different clay bodies?
note = | Very adaptable to stoneware, porcelain, rough, smooth, etc.
note = |
note = |*What consistency should the glaze be for pouring/dipping?
note = | Dip hand into bucket; can hardly see skin under glaze on hand: thick
note = |cream.
note = |
note = |*How thickly should the glaze be applied to the pot?
note = | Varies with oxide addition.  Likes to be moderately thick for
note = |richest results.
note = |
note = |*How does this glaze interact with other glazes?
note = | I had not been happy with combining it with others, so I stopped. It
note = |can be layered with itself with different colorants in each layer.
note = |
note = |*What is your kiln type and size?
note = | 10 cubic foot, Tucker's Cone Art, electric
note = |
note = |*How do you typically fire?
note = | 0 to 212 in two hours: hold 10 minutes.
note = | 212 to 1040 at about 300 degrees an hour.
note = | very slowly from 1040 to 1070.
note = | as quickly as possible from 1070 to 2100.
note = | about 150 degrees an hour until cone 7-8.
note = |
note = |*Do you experience problems with the raw glaze?
note = | no problems
