note = | This glaze is a very wonderful red, but like all reds, it's very
note = |temperamental.  A heavy reduction at the end is recommended.  Firing
note = |time should be between 12 and 20 hours.  Not enough reduction during
note = |the firing will cause the glaze to be clear.
note = |
note = |*How long have you been using this glaze?
note = | I've used this glaze off and on for 2 years.
note = |
note = |*Where is it used?
note = | University of Houston
note = |
note = |*Where did this recipe come from?
note = | This could be a Carlton Ball glaze, but I'm not sure.
note = |
note = |*Is this glaze reliable?
note = | The firing process is what's difficult about this glaze.  You should
note = |start reducing around cone 5 and do a heavy reduction at the end.
note = |
note = |*Does this glaze tend to craze/crawl/pinhole/etc.?
note = | You should make sure the surface of the pot is clean of dust.
note = |
note = |*How do different firing temperatures/atmospheres affect the glaze?
note = | Too muddy of a reduction will cause the copper to burn out.  Too
note = |little will cause the glaze to run clear.
note = |
note = |*How does the glaze behave on different clay bodies?
note = | White or light bodies are best, but it does work on red clay bodies.
note = |
note = |*What consistency should the glaze be for pouring/dipping?
note = | Once you have mixed the glaze with water, you need to use it that
note = |day. A thick application is best. Dipped if possible.  Once mixed the
note = |elements settle out and will not work if remixed.
note = |
note = |*How thickly should the glaze be applied to the pot?
note = | The thicker the better, but the glaze will run.
note = |
note = |*How does this glaze interact with other glazes?
note = | It works great with rutile glazes.
note = |
note = |*What is your kiln type and size?
note = | I used an updraft reduction kiln about 9 cubic feet.
note = |
note = |*How do you typically fire?
note = | I build temperature up to a cone 6 then reduce there for an hour,
note = |then go the rest of the way up reducing all the way.  With a heavy
note = |reduction at the end.  Then let it cool completely with all holes
note = |plugged and dampers shut tight.
note = |
note = |*Do you experience problems with the raw glaze?
note = | Keep materials dry until you are ready to use.  It will not stay
note = |mixed and the chemicals alter if left wet for more than 48 hours.
note = |
