note = |Note that this glaze did not have a cone specified, but it appears to
note = |be a cone 9 glaze. I do not have experience with crystalline glazes
note = |but I do know of an excellent article that appeared in Ceramic Review
note = |No.137 (Sept/Oct 1992) by Derek Clarkson. His recipes are all based
note = |on the previous approximate percentages. The china clay was listed as
note = |China Clay/Alumina Colouring Oxides - cobalt, copper and manganese
note = |most often used, followed by iron and nickel. The article gives ten
note = |specific recipes around the above with colour illustrations to show
note = |the very dramatic crystal effects. For each of these examples the
note = |article also gives the firing details of the times of crystal growing
note = |periods and the diameter of the largest crystal. There is also a mass
note = |of detail on the application of the glazes with copious
note = |illustrations. Derek Clarkson says that Porcelain bodies are the most
note = |suitable. White stoneware bodies can also be used but the crystals
note = |are smaller. If you are unable to get sight of a copy of this article
note = |please contact me by e-mail if you want further information.
