note = |I have a revised glaze for you. But first let
note = |me tell you a bit about your current recipe. As you gave it, this
note = |glaze is a high alkaline earth glaze, a bit low in alumina, but
note = |otherwise smack in the midfire range c4-c7. It's unusual in the fact
note = |that it has 5.2% Titanium oxide and this will cause problems,
note = |pinholing being one of them. The glaze is prone to pinholing because
note = |there's too much carbonate in the raw materials. The COE at 7.2 is a
note = |bit high but it could well fit a stoneware of 6.+ COE. Ok. Here's the
note = |new version. This version closely matches the Unity Formula of your
note = |original. I have switched to Wollastonite and Talc to reduce the
note = |carbonate level. You could also use copper oxide black 40 units, or
note = |copper oxide red, 35 units and reduce the carbonate a bit more but
note = |the copper oxides are very hard to disperse and you may get speckling
note = |if you do not thoroughly screen the mix. The gerstley borate is
note = |higher than I'd wish but if I use Ferro frit 3134 (or 3195) in its
note = |place the alumina goes up almost 50% and the KNaO content goes up
note = |too, increasing the COE to 7.7 or higher; the glaze could craze
note = |markedly. The best course would be to try this mix first and see if
note = |it gives you the blue-green you want without pinholes. If out-gassing
note = |is still a problem, then perhaps one could use half Gerstley B and
note = |half 3195. I suggest, if this sits ok with you, that you go this
note = |route and see what happens and only make a further revision if
note = |needed. Tom Buck <aa563@main.freenet.hamilton.on.ca> Sana's Green is
note = |actually a C10R recipe that I posted here a while back because I was
note = |having pinhole problems with it. Here's the
note = |C10R version that Tom put together for me.  Richard Los Angeles from richard gralnik
note = |<rlg@patuxent.desktalk.com>

