note = |We've been having a terrible time with one of our production glazes.
note = |We've used it for several years without a problem, but after moving a
note = |year ago we started getting major blisters. Some firings are ok, then
note = |we'll have a terrible load even tho we fire the same schedule each
note = |time. We thot it might be the new water (it's softer, so we wondered
note = |if it might have more sodium), but tried the 'old' water, got the
note = |same blisters, altho not as bad (for a load or 2). We typically fire
note = |(propane) to ^10 tip touching, in about 11-12 hours) start reduction
note = |at ^012 at the coolest spot in the kiln. We take an hour from ^9 to
note = |^10, then usually leave the damper open for an hour to quick cool
note = |before we close it. We tried closing it immediately for a slow cool,
note = |hoping to smooth out the glaze, but still had blisters and had lost
note = |all our great blues. The temp is within 1/2 cone throughout the kiln,
note = |and reduction seems fairly even. The other thing is that it isn't
note = |every pot in that glaze. On one shelf, the pots on one side might be
note = |blistered and the other side fine, and one shelf up or down the
note = |opposite side is affected. It seems worse when the glaze is thin.
note = |Sometimes a re-fire helps smooth them out. Our 2 claybodies are
note = |Plainsman H443 (brown) and H551 (white). Could it be the clay? We
note = |have some blisters in other glazes too, altho not as bad. The only
note = |common ingredient in custer spar. I hope I've given you enough info
note = |to help me. It's been a year of seconds, losing about 20%. submitted
note = |by: Barb & Ray Sapergia e-mail: sapergia@island.net
