note = |*How long have you been using this glaze?
note = | Over 7 years
note = |
note = |*Where is it used?
note = | My studio
note = |
note = |*Where did this recipe come from?
note = | CM compilation of glazes.  Sorry, date unknown, but older than 10
note = |years.
note = |
note = |*What do you like most about this glaze?
note = | Consistency - apply thickly and it stays put.  Good for tableware.
note = |
note = |*Is this glaze reliable?
note = | ABSOLUTELY
note = |
note = |*Does this glaze tend to craze/crawl/pinhole/etc.?
note = | Rub any pinholes on dry glaze to avoid pinholing in final product.
note = |Wear gloves as this glaze will stain your hands - and your clothing.
note = |
note = |*How do different firing temperatures/atmospheres affect the glaze?
note = | Will fire to ^9 (gets glossy) but the colour is awful! Firing to ^10
note = |at 4 o'clock for best results.
note = |
note = |*How does the glaze behave on different clay bodies?
note = | Have used on 3 different clay bodies with identical results.
note = |
note = |*What consistency should the glaze be for pouring/dipping?
note = | Medium thick
note = |
note = |*How thickly should the glaze be applied to the pot?
note = | Medium thick - if applied thinly, you can get some red flashes - but
note = |unless clay is extremely smooth (non-stoneware) the end product is
note = |non-functional.
note = |
note = |*How does this glaze interact with other glazes?
note = | Overlapping with Penland opal gives a wonderful "chun" effect in ox.
note = |
note = |*What is your kiln type and size?
note = | PSH CRT 180 - 6.5 cubic ft.
note = |
note = |*How do you typically fire?
note = | I "candle" overnight. 20-24 hours depending on electricity demands.
note = |
note = |*Do you experience problems with the raw glaze?
note = | Rapid settling!!  I use .25 - .5% macaloid as a suspender - or it
note = |becomes a cement lump.  Also, takes a long time to dry.  Be patient!
note = |
note = |*What is your water pH?
note = | I use R/O water
note = |
