note = | This is an excellent transparent/clear glaze that is very hard and
note = |durable. I have used it over colored slip, with sgraffito into the
note = |slip and with oxides and stains brushed over it and the decorations
note = |don't move. This glaze can be brought to the VERY edge of the foot
note = |without moving. I use it inside of all my functional work and when
note = |decorating with colored slips I use it over the whole surface of the
note = |pot.
note = | It is an excellent glaze that will always perform well especially
note = |when you are in a hurry to get things fired. No surprises.
note = | Food-safe.
note = |
note = |*Variations:
note = | Can add 1/4 % Copper Carbonate for Light Green in Oxidation ^9-10
note = |firing.
note = |
note = |*How long have you been using this glaze?
note = | Almost 20 years
note = |
note = |*Where is it used?
note = | In my studio
note = |
note = |*Where did this recipe come from?
note = | I got this recipe from Kieth Campbell from Ontario, Canada but
note = |believe that it is an Alfred Univ. glaze originally
note = |
note = |*What do you like most about this glaze?
note = | There are no surprises and I can count on it every time. Its food
note = |safe.
note = |
note = |*Is this glaze reliable?
note = | Very
note = |
note = |*Does this glaze tend to craze/crawl/pinhole/etc.?
note = | Crazes if applied TOO THICK.
note = |
note = |*How do different firing temperatures/atmospheres affect the glaze?
note = | Electric/Oxidation or Gas fired/Reduction or neutral fire are all
note = |equally as good.
note = |
note = |*How does the glaze behave on different clay bodies?
note = | On porcelain and white stoneware it is clear white. On buff and or
note = |red bodies it goes somewhat grey because of the iron in the clays.
note = |Very pleasent on all clays. I have tested and used on all the above
note = |clays.
note = |
note = |*What consistency should the glaze be for pouring/dipping?
note = | The consistancy of my glazes is like homo milk. The normal
note = |consistancy. I dip to the count of 5 - 10.
note = |
note = |*How thickly should the glaze be applied to the pot?
note = | Normal.
note = | I spray this glaze as well to 1/16th of an inch or better.
note = |
note = |*How does this glaze interact with other glazes?
note = | I like it the way it is for my work.  Test your glazes and see what
note = |happens. I have sprayed other glazes on rims etc. and all worked fine.
note = |
note = |*What is your kiln type and size?
note = | 30 cu.ft. downdraft gas kiln.
note = |
note = |*How do you typically fire?
note = | Heating...pilots (4) on over night or at least a 9 hour period.
note = |Burners (4) on low over night or till cone 07 is down. Turn up the
note = |burners to 1/2 way mid. reduce kiln for 30 to 45 mins. depending on
note = |the weather.  Cut the reduction (open dampers to almost open and a
note = |light reduction till cone 10 falls. Clear kiln, shut off and seal.
note = | Slow 36 hour cool before cracking the door and work comes out in
note = |about 48 hours.
note = |
note = |*Do you experience problems with the raw glaze?
note = | NO....this glaze can be stirred easily even after 8 weeks of non use
note = |and stays stirred for long periods of time while glazing. I make a
note = |large green garbage pail of my well used glazes and they last me for
note = |a yr. or more.  No smells etc.
note = |
note = |*What is your water pH?
note = | City water.
note = |
note = |*Any other comments?
note = | Try this glaze...it will be a main stay in your studio. ;>}}}
