note = |*How long have you been using this glaze?
note = | 3years
note = |
note = |*Where is it used?
note = | Studio
note = |
note = |*Where did this recipe come from?
note = | From our own experimentation using the base recipe of our glaze
note = |named Mag as a starting point.
note = |
note = |*What do you like most about this glaze?
note = | The  color is very appealing and conservative-like. The surface is
note = |semi-gloss with a few speckles and nice to the touch; a very smooth
note = |surface.
note = |
note = |*Is this glaze reliable?
note = | Yes
note = |
note = |*Does this glaze tend to craze/crawl/pinhole/etc.?
note = | No surface flaws.
note = |
note = |*How do different firing temperatures/atmospheres affect the glaze?
note = | Not tested.
note = |
note = |*How does the glaze behave on different clay bodies?
note = | Well.
note = |
note = |*What consistency should the glaze be for pouring/dipping?
note = | Medium
note = |
note = |*How thickly should the glaze be applied to the pot?
note = | Medium
note = |
note = |*How does this glaze interact with other glazes?
note = | Not tested
note = |
note = |*What is your kiln type and size?
note = | Downdraft, propane and atmospheric,60 cubic feet.
note = |
note = |*How do you typically fire?
note = | Oxidation until clay reduction at cone 08, then a light reduction
note = |increasing with time until the final and total reduction of 20
note = |minutes followed by a 20 minute period of reoxidation
note = |
note = |*Do you experience problems with the raw glaze?
note = | No
note = |
note = |*What is your water pH?
note = | 7.2
note = |
note = |*Any other comments?
note = | I really like that glaze.
note = |
