note = |From Pete Pinnell, Clay Times Mar/Apr 2005 p. 21. The phosphorus contributes a
note = |number of qualifies to the glaze. It is a glass-former (like the silica), but the
note = |phosphorus and silica don't like to mix together (sort of like oil and water).
note = |This means that in the firing, the phosphorus tends to separate out and form a
note = |cloudy, slightly opalescent milkiness that I find very interesting. It also has a
note = |strong tendency to re-oxidize colorants in a glaze, which can result in unusual,
note = |vivid colors that have the richness of reduction firing, combined with the
note = |intensity of oxidation colors. A side effect of the phosphorus is that the glaze
note = |now resists going matte. It will if pushedthat is, if the cooling is slow enough,
note = |or if the piece is refired in a bisque kiln to allow enough time for the matting
note = |crystals to grow. Otherwise, it is a glossy glaze. The next step (after coming up
note = |with the base glaze) was to try out all the common glaze colorants and see what
note = |they did in this glaze. The results are fascinating, and many are beautiful. I'm
note = |currently in the process of developing more complex colors involving multiple
note = |oxides, and I'll pass those along in a future column.
note = |
note = |If you've ever mixed a tomato red glaze, you'll notice that it always includes a
note = |source of magnesium (such as talc or dolomite) and either natural or synthetic
note = |bone ash (a source of phosphorus). Together with iron and the other components,
note = |these create iron crystals, and push them into an oxidized state. As I suspected
note = |it would, Pete's CIA produces a bright tomato red with 7 or 8% red iron oxide. As
note = |the amount of iron increases to 10 or 11%, the glaze becomes quite crystalline,
note = |but just a bit more brown. The red can be made brighter by refiring it (after the
note = |glaze firing) in a bisque firing, or in any low-fire oxidation firing.2 Manganese
note = |dioxide makes a beautiful yellow (really!) in small percentages, becoming a creamy
note = |red-amber at higher percentages. Copper carbonate, which normally wants to turn a
note = |pink or red color in reduction, instead produces light blue-green to emerald
note = |green. It works from 1 to 9%. Titanium dioxide or ruffle produce very nice
note = |breaking and mottling, working best at 4 and 5%. The effect shows up best on
note = |stoneware, but also works well on porcelain with the addition of a small amount of
note = |another oxide (iron or copper, for instance) in addition to the titania. Tin oxide
note = |produces white at smaller percent-ages, which begins to break rust on edges (even
note = |on porcelain) as it nears 10%, with very pronounced cream and orange colors pro-
note = |duced on stoneware at 10% and 12%. Like the iron colors I mentioned above, it will
note = |become more orange when refired in a bisque or other low-fire oxidation firing.
note = |Frankly, I thought the results from cobalt and chrome were very boring, but that
note = |might be my taste in colors. Cobalt produced pasty, pastel blues. Chrome was nice
note = |in very tiny amounts0.3% made a nice, very light blue-green, but larger amounts
note = |produced dull greenish browns. Please keep in mind that this is a new glaze, and I
note = |don't have extensive experience with it. I've used it (in several color
note = |variations) in a half dozen or so firings, and it is very promising, but I have
note = |yet to work out all the bugs of application and firing.

